HashTables is a data structure that stores unique keys to values ex.<Integer, String>
Each key/value pair is kwown as an Entry
Fast insertion, look up, deletion of key/value pairs
Not ideal for small data sets, great with large data sets


Hash Collision --> when the % of a hashCode key is the same number of another

hashing = takes a key and computes an integer (formula will vary based on key & data type)
In a Hashtable, we use hash % capacity to calculate an index number

key.hashCode() % capacity = index

We can call some values in the same index as a "Bucket" this bucket it's like a linked list an entry points
to another ( linear search O(n) )

bucket = an indexed storage location for one or more Entries.
can store multiple Entries in case of a collision (linked similarly a LinkedList)

collision = hash function generates the same index for more than one key
            less collisions = more efficiency

To reduce the collisions you can grow the hashTable, but it will increase the memory that it has.
--> Load factor --> common 0.75 --> when the hashTable length reachs 75% it will increase,
usually the capacity will duplicate.

Runtime complexity: Best case O(1)
                    Worst case O(n)
                    